import java.io.File;
import java.io.IOException;

public class VulnerableCode {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Vulnerable code: using a relative path to load a file
        File file = new File("C:\\path\\to\\sensitive\\file.txt");
        String fileContent = new String(file.listFiles()[0].getAbsolutePath());
        System.out.println(fileContent);
    }
}
```
This code is vulnerable because it uses a relative path to load a file, which can lead to a path traversal attack. An attacker could manipulate the file path to access sensitive files on the system.

***

[code snippet 2]
```java
import java.io.File;
import java.io.IOException;

public class SecureCode {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Secure code: using a absolute path to load a file
        File file = new File("C:\\path\\to\\allowed\\file.txt");
        String fileContent = new String(file.listFiles()[0].getAbsolutePath());
        System.out.println(fileContent);
    }
}
```
This code is secure because it uses an absolute path to load a file, which makes it more difficult for an attacker to manipulate the file path and access sensitive files.

Note that in a real-world scenario, you would want to validate and sanitize user input to prevent path traversal attacks. Additionally, you should always use a secure way to load files, such as using a `FileInputStream` and specifying the file path and name explicitly.

